ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An important supervisory center in the brain, rich in ganglia, nerve fibers, and synaptic connections. It is composed of several sections called nuclei, each of which controls a specific function. The hypothalamus regulates body temperature, blood pressure, heartbeat, metabolism of fats and carbohydrates, and sugar levels in the blood. Through direct attachment to the pituitary gland, the hypothalamus also meters secretions controlling water balance and milk production in the female. The role of the hypothalamus in awareness of pleasure and pain is well established in the laboratory. It is involved in the expression of emotions, such as fear and rage, and in sexual behaviors. Despite its numerous vital functions, the hypothalamus in humans accounts for only 1/300 of total brain weight, and is about the size of an almond. Structurally, it is joined to the thalamus; the two work together to monitor the sleep-wake cycle.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An area within the dura sheath but outside of the spinal cord.: The portion of the spinal cord located in the thoracic region.

Concepts.definition: An area within the dura sheath but outside of the spinal cord.
The portion of the spinal cord located in the thoracic region.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A thin membrane that lines the fluid-filled spaces in the brain and spinal cord. It is made up of a type of glial cell called an ependymal cell.

Concepts.definition: A thin membrane that lines the ventricles of the brain and the central canal of the spinal cord.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The terminal, cone-shaped end of the spinal cord.

Concepts.definition: The terminal, cone-shaped end of the spinal cord.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Not characterized in any other way.: An irregularly shaped cavity in the rhombencephalon, between the medulla oblongata, the pons, and the isthmus in front, and the cerebellum behind. It is continuous with the central canal of the cord below and with the CEREBRAL AQUEDUCT above, and through its lateral and median apertures it communicates with the subarachnoid space.

Concepts.definition: Not characterized in any other way.
A diamond-shaped cavity filled with cerebrospinal fluid within the pons extending between the obex in the caudal medulla and the aqueduct of Sylvius in the cerebellum.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A continuation of the optic nerves just dorsal to the optic chiasm, formed by temporal fibers of the ipsilateral optic nerve and nasal fibers of the contralateral optic nerve, that carries axons to nuclei within the thalamus and relays visual information to the primary visual cortex of the occipital lobe.

Concepts.definition: A continuation of the optic nerves just dorsal to the optic chiasm, formed by temporal fibers of the ipsilateral optic nerve and nasal fibers of the contralateral optic nerve, that carries axons to nuclei within the thalamus and relays visual information to the primary visual cortex of the occipital lobe.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: One of the supratentorial cisterns. It is also called parasellar supratentorial cistern.

Concepts.definition: One of the supratentorial cisterns. It is also called parasellar supratentorial cistern.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The cranial nerve that controls the superior oblique muscle of the eye.

Concepts.definition: The cranial nerve that controls the superior oblique muscle of the eye.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The tenth cranial nerve. It is the longest cranial nerve. It originates in the medulla and exits the cranium through the jugular foramen. It supplies various muscles, including muscles of the pharynx and soft palate.

Concepts.definition: The tenth cranial nerve. It is the longest cranial nerve. It originates in the medulla and exits the cranium through the jugular foramen. It supplies various muscles, including muscles of the pharynx and soft palate.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A medial narrow structure connecting the two hemispheres of the cerebellum.

Concepts.definition: A medial narrow structure connecting the two hemispheres of the cerebellum.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The eighth cranial nerve composed of the acoustic nerve and the vestibular nerve. The nerve travels from the inner ear, enters the cranial cavity through the internal auditory foramen and joins the brainstem. The auditory nerve conveys impulses from the cochlea of the inner ear to the auditory nuclei of the brainstem. The vestibular nerve carries information from the labyrinths of the inner ear to the vestibular nuclei of the brainstem.

Concepts.definition: The eighth cranial nerve composed of the acoustic nerve and the vestibular nerve. The nerve travels from the inner ear, enters the cranial cavity through the internal auditory foramen and joins the brainstem. The auditory nerve conveys impulses from the cochlea of the inner ear to the auditory nuclei of the brainstem. The vestibular nerve carries information from the labyrinths of the inner ear to the vestibular nuclei of the brainstem.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Space between the dura mater and the walls of the vertebral canal.

Concepts.definition: Space between the dura mater and the walls of the vertebral canal.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Occurring in, or located within the spinal cord or the marrow space of a bone.: The portion of the spinal cord located in the cervical region.

Concepts.definition: Occurring in, or located within the spinal cord or the marrow space of a bone.
The portion of the spinal cord located in the cervical region.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Occurring in, or located within the spinal cord or the marrow space of a bone.: The portion of the spinal cord located in the lumbar region.

Concepts.definition: Occurring in, or located within the spinal cord or the marrow space of a bone.
The portion of the spinal cord located in the lumbar region.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Outside of, or unrelated to, any medulla, especially the medulla oblongata.: The portion of the spinal cord located in the lumbar region.

Concepts.definition: Outside of, or unrelated to, any medulla, especially the medulla oblongata.
The portion of the spinal cord located in the lumbar region.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An area within the dura sheath but outside of the spinal cord.: The portion of the spinal cord located in the lumbar region.

Concepts.definition: An area within the dura sheath but outside of the spinal cord.
The portion of the spinal cord located in the lumbar region.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The 7th cranial nerve. The facial nerve has two parts, the larger motor root which may be called the facial nerve proper, and the smaller intermediate or sensory root. Together they provide efferent innervation to the muscles of facial expression and to the lacrimal and salivary glands, and convey afferent information for taste from the anterior two-thirds of the tongue and for touch from the external ear. (MeSH)

Concepts.definition: Cranial nerve VII, which originates in the brainstem between the pons and the medulla. It controls the facial expression muscles and transports taste and sensation from the tongue and mouth.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Determination of a value is not relevant in the current context.

Concepts.definition: Determination of a value is not relevant in the current context.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The 6th cranial nerve. The abducens nerve originates in the abducens nucleus of the pons and sends motor fibers to the lateral rectus muscles of the eye. Damage to the nerve or its nucleus disrupts horizontal eye movement control.

Concepts.definition: A cranial nerve that supplies motor impulses to the lateral rectus muscle of the eye.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The 11th cranial nerve, which sends motor impulses to the muscles of the upper thorax, back, shoulders, and pharynx.

Concepts.definition: The 11th cranial nerve, which sends motor impulses to the muscles of the upper thorax, back, shoulders, and pharynx.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The outer layer of the cerebrum composed of neurons and unmyelinated nerve fibers.  It is responsible for memory, attention, consciousness and other high mental functions.

Concepts.definition: The outer layer of the cerebrum composed of neurons and unmyelinated nerve fibers. It is responsible for memory, attention, consciousness and other higher levels of mental function.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The part of the brain that controls muscle functions and also controls speech, thought, emotions, reading, writing, and learning. The right hemisphere controls the muscles on the left side of the body, and the left hemisphere controls the muscles on the right side of the body.

Concepts.definition: The part of the brain that controls muscle functions and also controls speech, thought, emotions, reading, writing, and learning. The right hemisphere controls the muscles on the left side of the body, and the left hemisphere controls the muscles on the right side of the body.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Definition not available.

Concepts.definition: The largest of the three principle cisterns in the subarachnoid space which is located between the cerebellum and the medulla oblongata.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A laminar extension of the dura mater that lies between, and separates, the cerebrum and the cerebellum.

Concepts.definition: A dural partition that separates the occipital lobes of the cerebrum from the cerebellum and divides the cranial cavity into supratentorial and infratentorial compartments; it helps to stabilize the brain within the cranial cavity.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A double-fold of dura mater that lies within the medial longitudinal fissure, and which separates the two cerebral hemispheres. It is attached rostrally to the crista galli and caudally to the surface of the tentorium cerebelli.

Concepts.definition: A double-fold of dura mater that lies within the medial longitudinal fissure, and which separates the two cerebral hemispheres. It is attached rostrally to the crista galli and caudally to the surface of the tentorium cerebelli.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Located within a ventricle of the brain or heart.

Concepts.definition: Located within a ventricle of the brain or heart.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: One of  two strong processes of the sphenoid bone, which arise from the sides of the body, and are curved upward, laterally, and backward. The superior or cerebral surface of each greater wing forms part of the middle cranial fossa.

Concepts.definition: One of two strong processes of the sphenoid bone, which arise from the sides of the body, and are curved upward, laterally, and backward. The superior or cerebral surface of each greater wing forms part of the middle cranial fossa.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Cranial cavity between the brow and nose in the frontal area of the brain.

Concepts.definition: Cranial cavity between the brow and nose in the frontal area of the brain.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Area within the sulci of the brain, usually anterior to the rolandic fissure.

Concepts.definition: Area within the sulci of the brain, usually anterior to the rolandic fissure.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A medial line, especially the medial line or medial plane of the body (or some part of the body).

Concepts.definition: A medial line, especially the medial line or medial plane of the body (or some part of the body).
